<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1156,1576]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,1300,1325]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[507,730,1300,1325]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="trachyderma">
<emphasis box="[507,730,1300,1325]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Anolis trachyderma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to Amazonia, with disjunct distribution in western Amazonia (between the Japurá and Juruá river basins), and in eastern Amazonia (restricted to the Tapajós–Xingu interfluvium), occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[463,534,1372,1397]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[548,661,1372,1397]" name="Colombia" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[674,769,1372,1397]" name="Ecuador" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[832,883,1373,1396]" name="Peru" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[901,969,1372,1397]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1103,1125]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,183,1073]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,173,1082]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distribution of examined material of Anolis philopunctatus, A. phyllorhinus and A. trachyderma." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/234985/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[955,969,1372,1397]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
) In 
<collectingCountry box="[1020,1088,1372,1397]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Brazil</collectingCountry>
it is known from the states of Pará, Amazonas, and Acre. 
<taxonomicName box="[482,708,1407,1432]" class="Reptilia" family="Dactyloidae" genus="Anolis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="trachyderma">
<emphasis box="[482,708,1407,1432]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Anolis trachyderma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is predominantly terrestrial and diurnal, inhabits primary and secondary terra firme and varzea forests, occasionally found at forest edge (
<bibRefCitation author="Duellman" box="[999,1177,1444,1469]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Duellman, W. E. (1978) The biology of an equatorial herpetofauna in Amazonian Ecuador. Miscellaneous Publications, Museum of Natural History of University of Kansas, 65, 1 - 352." type="journal article" year="1978">
Duellman 
<number box="[1118,1177,1444,1468]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1978.0">1978</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Avila-Pires" box="[1189,1382,1444,1469]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Avila-Pires, T. C. S. (1995) Lizards of Brazilian Amazonia (Reptilia: Squamata). Zoologische Verhandelingen, 299, 1 - 706." type="journal article" year="1995">
Ávila-Pires 
<number box="[1323,1382,1444,1469]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Vitt" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Vitt, L. J., Avila-Pires, T. C. S., Zani, P. A. &amp; Esposito, M. C. (2002) Life in shade: the ecology of Anolis trachyderma (Squamata: Polychrotidae) in Amazonian Ecuador and Brazil, with comparisons to ecologically similar anoles. Copeia, 2002, 275 - 286. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1643 / 0045 - 8511 (2002) 002 [0275: LISTEO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">
Vitt 
<emphasis box="[151,207,1479,1504]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[214,274,1480,1504]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), where it is usually found on the ground, but also on low vegetation and small trees, generally below 
<number box="[1422,1436,1480,1504]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2.0">2</number>
meters high (
<bibRefCitation author="Vanzolini" box="[300,476,1516,1541]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Vanzolini, P. E. (1972) Miscellaneous notes on the ecology of some Brazilian lizards (Sauria). Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 26, 83 - 115." type="journal article" year="1972">
Vanzolini 
<number box="[417,476,1516,1540]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1972.0">1972</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dixon" box="[489,725,1516,1541]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Dixon, J. R. &amp; Soini, P. (1975) The reptiles of the upper Amazon Basin, Iquitos region, Peru. Part 1. Lizards and amphisbaenians. Milwaukee Public Museum, Contributions in Biology and Geology, 4, 1 - 58." type="journal article" year="1975">
Dixon &amp; Soini 
<number box="[666,725,1516,1541]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1975.0">1975</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dixon" box="[738,797,1516,1541]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Dixon, J. R. &amp; Soini, P. (1986) The reptiles of the upper Amazon Basin, Iquitos region, Peru. Milwaukee Public Museum, Milwaukee, 154 pp." type="book" year="1986">
<number box="[738,797,1516,1541]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1986.0">1986</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Avila-Pires" box="[810,1005,1516,1541]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Avila-Pires, T. C. S. (1995) Lizards of Brazilian Amazonia (Reptilia: Squamata). Zoologische Verhandelingen, 299, 1 - 706." type="journal article" year="1995">
Ávila-Pires 
<number box="[946,1005,1516,1541]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Vitt" box="[1018,1194,1516,1541]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Vitt, L. J., Zani, P. A. &amp; Esposito, M. C. (1999) Historical ecology of Amazonian lizards: implications for community ecology. Oikos, 87, 286 - 294. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2307 / 3546743" type="journal article" year="1999">
Vitt 
<emphasis box="[1068,1126,1516,1541]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1134,1194,1516,1540]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Vitt" box="[1207,1268,1516,1540]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Vitt, L. J., Avila-Pires, T. C. S., Zani, P. A. &amp; Esposito, M. C. (2002) Life in shade: the ecology of Anolis trachyderma (Squamata: Polychrotidae) in Amazonian Ecuador and Brazil, with comparisons to ecologically similar anoles. Copeia, 2002, 275 - 286. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1643 / 0045 - 8511 (2002) 002 [0275: LISTEO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2002">
<number box="[1207,1268,1516,1540]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation box="[151,337,1551,1576]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Vitt, L. J., Avila-Pires, T. C. S., Zani, P. A. &amp; Esposito, M. C. (2002) Life in shade: the ecology of Anolis trachyderma (Squamata: Polychrotidae) in Amazonian Ecuador and Brazil, with comparisons to ecologically similar anoles. Copeia, 2002, 275 - 286. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1643 / 0045 - 8511 (2002) 002 [0275: LISTEO] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article">
Vitt 
<emphasis box="[200,249,1551,1576]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[270,329,1552,1576]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2002.0">2002</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
it shows a slight preference for low, damper areas within the forest.
</paragraph>
